	<transcript sound="sound1"><![CDATA[We can only control food poisoning when we understand what causes it.<br /><br />Food poisoning can be caused by biological and non-biological factors. <br /><br />Listed on screen are various causes of food poisoning.<br /><br />Hover over the graphics to find out whether each is a biological cause or a non-biological cause, and select each cause fore more details.]]></transcript>
	<transcript sound="pop1"><![CDATA[Bacterial food poisoning is by far the most common type, in some instances it may result in serious illness and even death.<br /><br />A large number of bacteria are usually involved, this is usually the result of them multiplying within food before consumption.]]></transcript>
	<transcript sound="pop2"><![CDATA[Viruses usually multiply in living cells, not in food or water.<br /><br />They are much smaller then bacteria and only a small number are usually required to cause illness.]]></transcript>
	<transcript sound="pop3"><![CDATA[Moulds are often responsible for the spoilage of food, especially baked products and fruit, frequently because of their prolonged unsatisfactory storage.<br /><br />However, some moulds produce mycotoxins which cause illness and even death, however this is rare.<br /><br />Foods involved include nuts, figs and apple juice.]]></transcript>
	<transcript sound="pop4"><![CDATA[Acute food poisoning from chemicals is rare and usually results from, poisonous chemicals being stored in unlabelled food containers, contamination of food by significant amounts of chemical for example, insecticides or cleaning agents, large amounts of chemical additives.]]></transcript>
	<transcript sound="pop5"><![CDATA[Acute metallic food poisoning is also quite rare and usually results from acid food or drink being in contact with certain metals such as copper, cadmium or zinc.<br /><br />Symptoms mainly include vomiting and abdominal pain, and usually develop within an hour.]]></transcript>
	<transcript sound="pop6"><![CDATA[Poisonous plants or fish rarely cause food poisoning in commercial premises.<br /><br />However, cases of poisoning from toadstools, tea contaminated with deadly nightshade, undercooked red kidney beans and the Japanese puffer fish have been recorded.<br /><br />Remember poisonous food may look, taste and smell completely normal.]]></transcript>
	

